gomodel:SYNGO_1015  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Authors use electrophoretic mobility shift assays (EMSAs) to detect the presence of kB-DNA-binding activities in the rat brain and rat synaptosomal preparations. They used a 32P-oligonucleoutide containing an NF-kB binding motif which was incubated with cell extracts and subjected to electrophoresis after the binding reaction to detect changes in motility. kB-binding activity was found in synaptosomal fractions with, but also without though less, treatment with DOC, which reveals latent kB-binding activities sequestered by IkB proteins. Previously, authors have described that p65/RelA complexes are responsible for kB-binding activities found in rat brain since incubation the IkB protein MAD3, which inhibits DNA-binding complexes containing p65 abolished the binding activities. The same effect was found when they used an antibody against the N terminus of p65, which also prevented DOC-activated complexes.. Experimental description: From M&M:\n-Male Wistar rats were used for preparation of tissue extracts, subcellular fractionation of brain and im- munofluorescence staining of cryosections.\n-The labeled DNA probe was a double- stranded oligonucleotide containing the NF-KB binding motif from the mouse K light chain enhancer (Promega)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0575-6950" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1585-539X" ;
        dc:date           "2018-05-30" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_1015" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

